This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring October 24, 2014, as United Nations Day. The proclamation highlights the founding of the United Nations in 1945 and its mission to maintain peace, encourage global cooperation, and promote human rights. It emphasizes the importance of the United Nations in addressing global challenges such as climate change, poverty eradication, armed conflict prevention, and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. The proclamation acknowledges the dedication and sacrifice of United Nations personnel, including humanitarian staff, peacekeepers, and health workers. It calls for strengthening and renewing the United Nations, choosing hope over fear, collaboration over division, and humanity over brutality. The proclamation concludes by urging the observance of United Nations Day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.